argsString:
{
  "_id": "pietroski_grounding",
  "tags": [
    "df"
  ],
  "props": {},
  "content": "Pietroski identified a simple and elegant way of generalising from the idea that an individual can be the agent of an action to the idea that an individual can be the agent of a larger event.\n(His account does require a minor correction, but this is not relevant here.)\nHis approach can be generalised to allow for any number of agents.\n% §± grounding #df\nLet us stipulate that events $D_1$, ...\\ $D_n$ \\emph{ground} $E$, if: $D_1$, ...\\ $D_n$ and $E$ occur;\n$D_1$, ...\\ $D_n$ are each (perhaps improper) parts of $E$; and\nevery event that is a proper part of $E$ but does not overlap $D_1$, ...\\ $D_n$ is caused by some or all of $D_1$, ...\\ $D_n$.\n% ",
  "source_file_info": {
    "path": "/Users/stephenbutterfill/Documents/writing/joint action julian kiverstein routledge handbook of the social mind",
    "basename": "joint_action.tex",
    "ext": ".tex",
    "modified": "2015-08-17T15:12:43.000Z"
  }
}

